		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Importance of Choosing a Site Marker<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.75)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7058'>Jonathan "Carny" brown</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7058&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 29, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Ahem.<br />
	Welcome to another(?) exciting(?) installment of articles from the Carny. In this episode, I will show everyone what is quite possibly the most important decision there is when preparing to play in a Lord of The Rings Trading Card Game tournament. This one aspect of your game can make or break you when it comes to high level play, just as it can when applied to local tournaments. But, you say, I’ve won plenty of games using just an odd colored bead from the twilight pool! Too true, but haven’t people won tournaments playing sub-par decks just out of sheer dumb luck? Haven’t talent-less no-bodies received fame and notoriety thanks to MTV(Carson Daily and Good Charlotte, I’m looking at you)? While it’s possibly to be somewhat successful at this game, nay life, without a proper site marker, deciding on a proper one can only help things in the end. <br />
	In order to diagnose your site marker needs, we must first analyze why you play this card game. For instance, do you feel that the game is boring and you only continue to play because you feel like you’re obligated to? Nah, no one like that is still reading. Ahem. Lets start over. Do you play for fun? A good sign of this would be if you often play decks that may not be overly powerful or competitive. Dwarves are a good indication of a player in it for fun. In this case, try to find something that will make others laugh. Perhaps a Homie from the fifty cent machine at the grocery store, from what I understand these little fellows have started to appear on the sites of some upper tier players, such as Clint Hays, so maybe a Homie is more serious that I originally thought :)<br />
If you play primarily for money, or just to win, then consider something angry and intimidating. Warhammer 40k has some impressive bug-like creatures that can be painted to be somewhat scary, and for a minimal investment. Lastly, for most players, you’ll just want to choose something that represents an area of your life that is not represented by Lord of the Rings. I know the temptation is to get a little Legolas, or a Hobbit or something, but I encourage you to look into the other areas of you life. Give people you don’t know a way to gaze into your soul(God, that sounds lame) where they might find something they have in common with you. Site markers make a great conversation starter at large tournaments where the tendency is to be too serious and not enjoy the game. <br />
	Now that we have chosen a kind of site marker, or at least gotten some clue as to what kind you should use, lets delve(heh) into the reasons that you should have one at all. Well, first and foremost, it is in the rules. The Rulebook mentions having something(they use a token) to represent where on the site path your fellowship is. Now that the obligatory reason is out of there, lets get away from it.<br />
<br />
     1)	Distraction<br />
     Distraction is a very important part of LOTR. Read Patrick Malbeouf’s TR from Essen and take note of the game where he fooled his opponent into forgetting about using Enquea. You can take this tactic out farther by using a site marker so outlandish that your opponent cannot think about anything except it. When I played in the Atlanta DPC last year, I played Trevor Bradly who was using some sort of weird Sex Toy as a site marker. I must say that I was made uncomfortable and consequently played a little below my skill level in that game. While I am not condoning the use of something so disgusting as a site marker, I think it hammers home the fact that a site marker can force your opponent to think about something other than the game. Some examples of distracting site markers that I would approve of(though some might approve of the sex toy) would be a Toy Biz Cave Troll, and a Heroclix Sentinel because they are huge. In fact the Cave Troll makes electronic noises, which you might get away with using in a local tourney. Other choices might be an action figure/sculpture that is either exceeding gross or somewhat sexy(stupid sexy Flanders!). You’d be surprised how “interested” some gamers can get thanks to a lump of plastic, or two lumps to be specific.<br />
     2)	Something to do while your opponent “thinks”<br />
     LOTR requires thinking, but only to a certain degree. While some my bash Lord of the Rings as a game without enough actual game actions, I myself find it to have just enough to make things interesting, without giving me an aneurysm like Star Wars was prone to(proceed with the flaming). I find that now, without Sting to show you what you’re up against every turn, there are more things to consider when making a move, but that being said, c’mon! We’ve all played(or been) the guy that sits there when you know he’s dead(or you’re dead) and thinks for LITTERALY 20 minutes trying to figure out what to do. It’s even worse when it’s not a situation that even matters. In this spot, wouldn’t you like to have a little rubber hamster you can pet soothingly, who you can assure everything will be alright? Well, I know I would. Bastards. Some good choices might be a Toy Biz Bendy Gollum(you can re-inact his personal argument) or a slinky(everyone loves a slinky!).<br />
     3)	A Glimpse into……you!<br />
     Ever sit down across from an opponent and feel a certain….tension? A bit what the French call a certain I don’t know what(yes, I stole the joke)? This problem can sometimes be remedied by choosing a site marker that represents something you enjoy. Rather than spending an entire game where you glare across at your opponent, plotting his demise, you may have something in common with them. Like Batman? Maybe your opponent does to, and you can debate the merits of DK2 with him as you run to Orthanc!<br />
I cannot really give some options, but some of my favorite site markers are Transformers Heroes of Cybertron(I’m partial to Starscream, but who isn’t?) and Hamtaro. I have no idea what that says about me. Doctor?<br />
     4)	Protest<br />
     I know some players feel strongly about certain political issues. Well, here’s your chance to rally the cause!  I know this issue might not seem that common, but perusing the DeckTech member pages, you’ll see a lot of people with strong personal opinions on everything to the American War on Terrorism to SARS to Liquifying Goldfish. I know for a fact that some of you have things to say. Some examples might be a button that say “Vote Dukhakis(sp?)” or “Captain America for President”. Perhaps “US out of Vietnam!” or even “Leave the Art in Smart!”. <br />
     5)	Winning<br />
     The final, and obviously most important, reason for choosing a proper site marker is to precipitate winning quicker and more easily. How, you ask, can a site marker have ANY impact, aside from distraction, on whether or not you lose your game. Well, I reply, they will talk to you. I cannot even count the number of times that I’ve been in a helpless situation and I’ve looked down at Hamtaro and made a helpless face. He then looks up at me and says “icka” which is the only thing a hamster can say, but suddenly I’ll realize what I need to do to salvage whatever hopeless situation I’m in. Even more often, I’ll be playing against a shadow culture I haven’t playtested against and Optimus Prime will look at me knowingly and, after consulting the Matrix of Leadership, he’ll get back to me with a strategy that will absolutely dominate whichever opponent I am pitted against. Site markers win games.<br />
<br />
    Since I have listed all of the good things, or at least most of them, about using a site marker, I feel obligated to point out some of the down sides to using a colorful, distracting, entertaining, or protesting site marker.  First of all, you can get in trouble for intentionally trying to distract you opponent from the game, whether it is with a site marker or not. In fact, it is probably on some level immoral to intentionally try to foil your opponent with a large hunk of plastic. There is a chance you could get a warning during, or even after, the tournament(especially if you mention it in a tournament report) for trying to distract an opponent with, say, a life-size Mini-Me doll that talks and poops it’s diaper. Secondly, you have to be careful not to choose a site marker that is too entertaining for you. I know I have missed countless maneuver and archery actions on my opponents turns when I get too wrapped up in the Etch-A-Sketch I brought to occupy my opponent’s thought time. These things can cost you a game. On the up side, I drew a REALLY cool set of stairs! On the subject of showing a part of your personality, which includes the political section, it can often have the opposite of the intended effect. Perhaps you love the Powerpuff Girls, well in choosing a Bubbles site marker(if you are NOT a Female) be prepared to be considered a little….how to phrase this……GAY. While it may not be the case, or you may be trying to get that across, it WILL have an effect on the attitude of the game. The same goes for strong opinions, since few players will likely agree with a controversial topic. More likely, gamers will not want to have the fact that strong issues exist brought to their attention. Finally, be wary of advice given to you by a site marker. I once had a See-N-Say that I relied on for advice, and it regularly told me “Green is for Grass” which, to me, meant “Triplemove with Frodo”. Losing ensued. Another example of a faulty site marker would be my girl-friend’s Wickett, which she uses often. Wickett, as we all know, is gay. He also has an affinity for hairy faced men, and will often give Noelle bad advice when she is facing an opponent with a beard, mustache or even peach fuzz. Be careful who you choose, a site marker can make or break you and must be used correctly to benefit the most from it.<br />
In closing, let me thank you for reading all the way through this incredibly deep and thoughtful article. I have poured my all into every word, except this one: Mule. I believe that the site marker is an oft-overlooked dimension to Decipher’s Lord of the Rings Trading Card Game that needs to be taken more seriously. If everyone would be as devoted and interested in which site marker they used as they are about their “deck” and their “gameplay” we could see this game through to the next level. A level of excellence akin to that juggernaught of gameplaying enjoyment “Ants in the Pants”<br />
Ahem.<br />
Thank You.<br />
<br />
The Carny<br />
